For my historical fantasy settings, I just ripped off the greeks with "and their gods took on their form" so the "eagle" pantheon has eagle gods, though in practice they are simply perceptions of the "form" of said god.

For Tribes
There are two levels of godhood
There is the two dreamers, that which was, that which will be, and the "dream" is now, called the present as it is a gift.
The gods were the first aspects of the dream to think, before that there was the abstractions of the dreamers. Eventually as more and more gods came to be as more concepts became known, ideas like "creation" and "sight" and "love" abstract concepts. Eventually the creator god, the shaper shapes animals, and the huntress goddess, originally the seeker, made the original forms of the all the living things in the world, until one day he shapes something in the likeness of a god, from there he shaped them to look like the animals he had made. With time as more and more gods came to exist as the thinkers of the world came to need new concepts, gods patronized certain races. The creator and the seeker gods are dead, at least partially.

If a race is conquered by another, their god can join a new pantheon or join the one of his people's conquer as his people and theirs are now bound as a concept. The former ensures rebellion, the latter ensure integration, as the souls of a people are bound to their god. In tribes, the gods of the lynx, raven, sheep, and certain cow deities are bound to the faceless god of man. Where "all that bears scales" is bound to the reptile chimera god of the sun. Its why fighting is skirmishes and raids or total war, sometimes a god will submit itself and its followers to another, like the ravens did as the faceless one was preferable to the goat gods.
So as much as the people of god give it form and power, the inverse it true as well. The gods also give those souls capable of magic the ability to wield it, excepting those that renounce their god.
